questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked

Tests knowledge of bit-twiddling tricks for 128-bit values without loops.

## Key Concepts

- SWAR/popcount for 64-bit chunks
- Safe 128-bit aggregation without branches

## Code Example

```c
uint32_t popcount128(uint64_t hi, uint64_t lo){
  auto count64 = [](uint64_t v){
    v = v - ((v>>1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL);
    v = (v & 0x3333333333333333ULL) + ((v>>2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL);
    v = (v + (v>>4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
    v = v + (v>>8);
    v = v + (v>>16);
    v = v + (v>>32);
    return (uint64_t)(v & 0x7F);
  };
  uint64_t c1 = count64(hi);
  uint64_t c2 = count64(lo);
  return (uint32_t)(c1 + c2);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this to a 256-bit value?
- What are the risks of using this in performance-critical hot paths compared to builtin intrinsics?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to apply known bit-hack patterns to solve a common problem without loops or libs. Shows understanding of data-parallel aggregation and portability across compilers.

## Key Concepts

- SWAR (SIMD Within A Register) counting
- Bit masks and shifts to sum bits in chunks
- Portability across 32-bit integers

## Code Example

```c
#include <stdint.h>
uint32_t countBits32(uint32_t x) {
  x = (x & 0x55555555) + ((x >> 1) & 0x55555555);
  x = (x & 0x33333333) + ((x >> 2) & 0x33333333);
  x = (x & 0x0F0F0F0F) + ((x >> 4) & 0x0F0F0F0F);
  x = (x & 0x00FF00FF) + ((x >> 8) & 0x00FF00FF);
  x = (x & 0x0000FFFF) + ((x >> 16) & 0x0000FFFF);
  return x;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt for 64-bit integers?
- What are alternative methods and trade-offs (lookup-table vs SWAR)?

