## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of 128-bit bit packing, non-overlapping fields, and in-place updates without loops. It exercises careful mask calculation and cross-boundary writes.

## Key Concepts
- Bit masks and clearing specific ranges
- Cross-boundary placement across lo/hi
- Safe in-place updates without branching
- Endianness-agnostic bit numbering

## Code Example
```c
void packHeader128(uint64_t hi, uint64_t lo, uint8_t A, uint16_t B, uint16_t C, uint32_t D, uint64_t *out_hi, uint64_t *out_lo) {
  uint64_t lo_mask = ((uint64_t)0xFF) | (((uint64_t)0xFFF) << 8) | (((uint64_t)0xFFFF) << 32);
  uint64_t hi_mask = ((uint64_t)0xFFFFFFFF) << 16;
  *out_lo = (lo & ~lo_mask) | (uint64_t)A | (((uint64_t)B) << 8) | (((uint64_t)C) << 32);
  *out_hi = (hi & ~hi_mask) | (((uint64_t)D) << 16);
}
``` 

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt if ranges could overlap and you needed deterministic behavior?
- How would you validate correctness across all inputs in a unit test?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to reduce a 128-bit value to a single parity bit using only bitwise ops, no branching.

## Key Concepts

