## Why This Is Asked

Tests understanding of bit pattern encoding, branchless 64-bit manipulation, and mask-driven bit dilation techniques. It evaluates consistency across endianness and fixed-width arithmetic skills.

## Key Concepts

- Branchless bit manipulation
- Fixed-width masks for progressive dilation
- 64-bit hexadecimal mask constants
- Bit-level reasoning and positional mapping

## Code Example

```c
uint64_t spread32to64(uint32_t x) {
    uint64_t y = x;

    // Progressive dilation using fixed masks
    y = (y | (y << 16)) & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL;
    y = (y | (y << 8))  & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL;
    y = (y | (y << 4))  & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
    y = (y | (y << 2))  & 0x3333333333333333ULL;
    y = (y | (y << 1))  & 0x5555555555555555ULL;

    // Duplicate each bit to adjacent position
    return y | (y << 1);
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests mastery of bit manipulation algorithms and performance optimization. The SWAR approach demonstrates understanding of parallel processing at the bit level and reveals trade-offs between naive implementations and optimized solutions.

## Key Concepts
- SWAR (SIMD Within A Register) for bit-level parallelism
- Strategic masking and shifting for parallel accumulation
- Branchless algorithms minimizing pipeline stalls
- Cross-platform compiler compatibility and correctness

## Code Example
```c
uint64_t popcount64(uint64_t x) { 
  x = x - ((x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL);
  x = (x & 0x3333333333333333ULL) + ((x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL);
  x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
  return (x * 0x0101010101010101ULL) >> 56;
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests knowledge of per-byte bit-twiddling, branchless design, and parallel bit tricks that map well to performance-critical code paths in systems programming.

## Key Concepts
- Byte-wide parity, parallel bit tricks, constant-time operations
- Masking to extract per-byte indicators
- No branches or loops

## Code Example
```c
uint64_t perByteParity64(uint64_t x) {
  uint64_t y = x;
  y ^= y >> 1;
  y ^= y >> 2;
  y ^= y >> 4;
  return y & 0x0101010101010101ULL;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
