- Can you adapt to compute even parity per byte instead of odd parity?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests understanding of 128-bit data manipulation, endianness, and composing simple bit tricks to achieve a larger transformation without loops.

## Key Concepts

- 128-bit value composed of two 64-bit halves
- Byte reversal within 64-bit words (endian swap)
- Combining results to form final 128-bit reversal
- No loops; relies on fixed-mask shifts

## Code Example

```javascript
uint64_t reverse64(uint64_t x){
  x = ((x & 0x00000000FFFFFFFFULL) << 32) | ((x & 0xFFFFFFFF00000000ULL) >> 32);
  x = ((x & 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL) << 16) | ((x & 0xFFFF0000FFFF0000ULL) >> 16);
  x = ((x & 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL) << 8)  | ((x & 0xFF00FF00FF00FF00ULL) >> 8);
  return x;
}

void endianSwap128(uint64_t hi, uint64_t lo, uint64_t *out_hi, uint64_t *out_lo){
  *out_hi = reverse64(lo);
  *out_lo = reverse64(hi);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you verify correctness for non-trivial patterns quickly?
- How does this approach scale if you extend to 256-bit values?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to perform cross-128-bit bit counting without loops, using portable bit-twiddling. Demonstrates knowledge of XOR for difference, and multi-word popcount without hardware intrinsics.

## Key Concepts

- XOR-based difference
- SWAR-style popcount on 64-bit words
- Combining counts for 128-bit data

## Code Example

```c
unsigned distance128(uint128 a, uint128 b) {
  uint64_t x = a.hi ^ b.hi;
  uint64_t y = a.lo ^ b.lo;
  // SWAR popcount on x
  x = x - ((x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL);
  x = (x & 0x3333333333333333ULL) + ((x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL);
  x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
  x = x + (x >> 8);
  x = x + (x >> 16);
  x = x + (x >> 32);
  // SWAR popcount on y
  y = y - ((y >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ULL);
  y = (y & 0x3333333333333333ULL) + ((y >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ULL);
  y = (y + (y >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
  y = y + (y >> 8);
  y = y + (y >> 16);
  y = y + (y >> 32);
  return (unsigned)(x & 0xFF) + (unsigned)(y & 0xFF);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you generalize to arbitrary n-word widths while maintaining no-loops constraints?
- Could you optimize using compiler intrinsics if available and fall back gracefully? If so, which intrinsics and how would you keep portability?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to manipulate multi-word integers with precise bit logic, no loops, and edge-case handling.

## Key Concepts
- 128-bit two-word shifts without loops
- x & ~(x<<1) to locate run-start bits
- 64-bit popcount for final tally

## Code Example
```c
uint64_t countOneRuns128(uint64_t hi, uint64_t lo) {
  uint64_t lo_shift = lo << 1;
  uint64_t hi_shift = (hi << 1) | (lo >> 63);
  uint64_t mask_lo = lo & ~lo_shift;
  uint64_t mask_hi = hi & ~hi_shift;
  return __builtin_popcountll(mask_lo) + __builtin_popcountll(mask_hi);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt this for counting 0-runs?
- What's the time complexity compared to a loop-based solution?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests mastery of non-trivial bit hacks and understanding of 8×8 transpose, a common optimization in graphics, crypto, and compression. It checks for precise, branchless manipulation and correct use of masks.

## Key Concepts
- fixed-sequence bit swaps
- 8×8 bit matrix representation
- mask constants, shifts, no loops

## Code Example
```cpp
uint64_t transpose64(uint64_t x) {
    const uint64_t m1  = 0x5555555555555555ULL;
    x = (x & m1) << 1 | (x >> 1) & m1;
    const uint64_t m2  = 0x3333333333333333ULL;
    x = (x & m2) << 2 | (x >> 2) & m2;
    const uint64_t m4  = 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0FULL;
    x = (x & m4) << 4 | (x >> 4) & m4;
    const uint64_t m8  = 0x00FF00FF00FF00FFULL;
    x = (x & m8) << 8 | (x >> 8) & m8;
    const uint64_t m16 = 0x0000FFFF0000FFFFULL;
    x = (x & m16) << 16 | (x >> 16) & m16;
    const uint64_t m32 = 0x00000000FFFFFFFFULL;
    x = (x & m32) << 32 | (x >> 32) & m32;
    return x;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test this with randomized 64-bit inputs to validate correctness?
- How would you generalize to 16×16 blocks with a 256-bit input stored in four 64-bit words?

## Why This Is Asked

Assesses ability to reason about cross-half bit patterns and leverage a reversal primitive to detect palindromicity without loops.

## Key Concepts

- 128-bit representations split across two 64-bit halves
- Cross-half bit equality, palindrome concept
- Using an existing reversal primitive to avoid per-bit work

## Code Example

```javascript
// Implementation sketch
int isPalindrome128(uint64_t hi, uint64_t lo) {
  uint64_t hi_rev, lo_rev;
  reverse128(hi, lo, &hi_rev, &lo_rev);
  return (hi == hi_rev && lo == lo_rev) ? 1 : 0;
}
```

