## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to reason with 128-bit data layout and perform blockwise rearrangements using only bitwise ops. It also checks handling of multi-word operands without branching.

## Key Concepts

- Block masking and extraction
- Cross-word recombination
- Branchless 128-bit manipulation

## Code Example

```c
typedef struct { uint64_t hi; uint64_t lo; } uint128;

uint128 swapAdjacentBlocks128(uint128 x, unsigned block) {
    uint64_t M = (1ULL << block) - 1;
    uint64_t A0 = x.lo & M;
    uint64_t A1 = (x.lo >> block) & M;
    uint64_t A2 = x.hi & M;
    uint64_t A3 = (x.hi >> block) & M;
    uint64_t loP = (A0 << block) | A1;
    uint64_t hiP = (A2 << block) | A3;
    return (uint128){.hi = hiP, .lo = loP};
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you extend to non-uniform block counts or dynamic block that isn't divisor of 128?
- How to optimize for block=16 across many values in tight loops?

