## Key Concepts
- Morton order interleaving
- Bit-slicing with masks and shifts (part1by1 technique)
- 64-bit to 128-bit composition without branches
- Endianness implications for MSB-first construction

## Code Example
```c
struct uint128_t {
    uint64_t hi, lo;
};

// Spread single bits to double-bit positions
static inline uint64_t part1by1(uint64_t x) {
    x = (x ^ (x << 16)) & 0x0000ffff0000ffff;
    x = (x ^ (x << 8))  & 0x00ff00ff00ff00ff;
    x = (x ^ (x << 4))  & 0x0f0f0f0f0f0f0f0f;
    x = (x ^ (x << 2))  & 0x3333333333333333;
    x = (x ^ (x << 1))  & 0x5555555555555555;
    return x;
}

struct uint128_t interleave64(uint64_t a, uint64_t b) {
    uint64_t a_spread = part1by1(a);
    uint64_t b_spread = part1by1(b);

    struct uint128_t result;
    result.lo = (a_spread << 1) | b_spread;
    result.hi = (a_spread >> 63) | (b_spread >> 63);
    return result;
}
```

This implementation uses the classic part1by1 technique to spread bits, then combines them with simple shifts and OR operations, achieving the required bit alternation without loops or conditionals.
